{
  "texts": [
    "If HyDRa's full version with Hessian vector products is used, Agarwal et al.'s (2017) Hessian approximation algorithm estimates each HVP in O(p) time and space.",
    "Therefore, the fast and standard versions of HyDRa both have full time complexity O(npT)-same as TracIn, albeit with potentially much worse constant factors.",
    "Observe that each hypergradient h(T) i only needs to be computed once and can be reused for each test instance.",
    "Therefore, the fast and standard version of HyDRa have incremental time complexity of just n gradient dot products-O(np) complexity total.",
    "This incremen- tal complexity is much faster than TracIn and asymptotically equivalent to influence functions."
  ]
}